n B, we compute the \"needed\" contribution for each contribA to get\n  // pivot vals. But we don't pick a specific contribA to match -- instead we just\n  // need to iterate over all contribA entries and compute the total.\n  //\n  // The saving comes when many A assignments map to the same contribA signature.\n  // We only keep the best A per signature, reducing the inner loop.\n  // #unique signatures <= min(sizeA, p^rank).\n  // With rank up to 40 and p up to 97, p^rank can be huge.\n  // But sizeA = p^halfA, and halfA ~ numFree/2.\n  // If numFree = 10 and p = 97, sizeA = 97^5 ~ 8.6 billion -- too large.\n  //\n  // Hmm. Let me reconsider. With 40 buttons and 40 counters, rank = 40,\n  // numFree = 0. The free variables only appear when we have more buttons than\n  // independent equations. With 40 lights constraining 40 buttons, if the system\n  // has full rank, numFree = 0.\n  //\n  // But we could have rank < numButtons if buttons are linearly dependent.\n  // In the worst case: 40 buttons, 0 lights, rank = 0, numFree = 40.\n  // With modulus 97, that's 97^40 -- no algorithm can enumerate this.\n  //\n  // But wait: if rank = 0 (no constraints), then ALL pivot values are zero,\n  // and we just need to minimize sum of free variable values.\n  // Each free variable independently contributes, and the minimum is when\n  // each is set to 0. So the answer is all zeros.\n  //\n  // More generally, if there are no pivot variables depending on the free variables,\n  // the minimum is always to set free variables to 0.\n  //\n  // If there ARE pivot variables, each pivot value depends on free variables.\n  // The cost for pivot row r is: (base[r] - sum(coeff[r][f] * free[f])) mod p\n  // The total cost is: sum(free[f]) + sum(pivot costs)\n  //\n  // This is an optimization over GF(p) which is NP-hard in general (closest vector problem).\n  // But with the constraint that rank + numFree = numButtons <= 40,\n  // and rank <= numCounters <= 40, the practical cases should be manageable.\n  //\n  // For the MITM approach to work, we need both halves to be tractable.\n  // p^(numFree/2) needs to be <= ~10M.\n  // For p=97, numFree/2 <= 3.5, so numFree <= 7.\n  // For p=2, numFree/2 <= 23, so numFree <= 46.\n  //\n  // For larger numFree with large modulus, we need yet another approach.\n  // But let's see: the problem says up to 40 buttons and 40 counters.\n  // If all 40 buttons are independent (rank=40), numFree=0. Unique solution.\n  // If buttons are very dependent, numFree could be large.\n  // But each free variable adds a degree of freedom. With p=97 and numFree=8,\n  // MITM has 97^4 ≈ 88M per side, which is borderline.\n  //\n  // Let me use a hybrid approach: MITM for moderate cases, and for very large\n  // cases, use an ILP-like approach or just note that those extreme cases\n  // are unlikely given the problem constraints.\n  //\n  // For now, let's implement a solid MITM that works for reasonable cases.\n\n  const sizeA = Math.pow(modulus, halfA);\n  const sizeB = Math.pow(modulus, halfB);\n\n  // Build table A: group by contribution signature\n  // contribA signature: array of rank values mod p -> encode as string\n  const tableA = new Map<string, { total: number; freeValues: number[] }>();\n\n  for (let combo = 0; combo < sizeA; combo++) {\n    const freeValues = new Array(halfA).fill(0);\n    let temp = combo;\n    for (let f = 0; f < halfA; f++) {\n      freeValues[f] = temp % modulus;\n      temp = Math.floor(temp / modulus);\n    }\n\n    // Compute contribution to each pivot row\n    const contribs: number[] = new Array(rank);\n    for (let r = 0; r < rank; r++) {\n      let c = 0;\n      for (let f = 0; f < halfA; f++) {\n        c = (c + matrix[r][freeVars[f]] * freeValues[f]) % modulus;\n      }\n      contribs[r] = c;\n    }\n\n    let partialTotal = 0;\n    for (let f = 0; f < halfA; f++) {\n      partialTotal += freeValues[f];\n    }\n\n    const key = contribs.join(',');\n    const existing = tableA.get(